When a small group of living beings are separated from the main population from which they originate (e.g. when moving over the mountain range or river, or when moving to a new island, without the possibility of easy withdrawal) they are often find themselves in a different environments than previously.
In this new environment, there are different resources and different competitors, so the new population will have to develop new properties or adapt in such a way that they can effectively compete in a new environment for themselves.
The original population has not changed a bit and still needs to adapt as well.
With time as the new population adapts to the new environment, it is becoming less and less like other populations.
At the end of the year, when thousands or even millions of years pass away, these two populations will be so different that it will be difficult to call them one species.
This process is called specialization, which simply means the formation of new species. Specialization is the inevitable result of evolution and its very important element.
