Technological determinism includes a wide range of ideas used in practice, including technological impulse or technological imperative, as well as a strict definition of human destiny guided by the hidden logic of scientific rights and technological manifestation.
Most interpretations of technological determinism combine two general principles: firstly, the process of technological development itself is not influenced by cultural or political factors, and secondly, technology generates effects in societies that are inherent and not socially conditioned.
For example, it can be said that a motor vehicle necessarily leads to the development of a road network.
